D21009 - D21039 - I2R ET

Problem Statement

Goal to predict the patient will get stroke or not by using health care data set.

Objective

Build a classification model to predict by using features from health care data set whether a patient gets stroke or not.

Variables Details

ID : Unique identifier

Gender: Gender of the patient

Age : Age of the patient

Hypertension: It referred as high blood pressure. 0 if he does not has Hypertension and 1 if he has it.

Heart disease: 0 if he does not has heart disease and 1 if he has it.

Ever married: “Yes” if he is married else “No”.

Work type: It gives the occupancy of a patient in 4 categories which are “Government”, “Never worked”, “Private” and “Self employed”.

Residence Type: It basically referred as area the patient lives in. Rural and Urban.

Average Glucose level: Average glucose level in blood of a patient.

BMI : Body mass index of the patient.

Smoking status: smoking status of patient. “Formerly smoked”, “Never smoked” and “Smokes”.

Stroke : Ultimate target variable which defined by the above variables.

Hypothesis:

Id doesn’t affect the patient condition.

Gender could affect the patient condition.

Age can effect a patient to get stroke.

Hypertension could effect the dependent variable stroke.

Heart Disease could effect the dependent variable stroke.

Marriage could effect the dependent variable stroke.

Work type could effect the dependent variable stroke.

Residence type could effect the dependent variable stroke.

Average glucose level could effect the dependent variable stroke.

Body mass index could effect the dependent variable stroke.

Smoking status could effect the dependent variable stroke.

iqr1 = IQR(newdata$avg_glucose_level)

glucose_outliers = newdata$avg_glucose_level[newdata$avg_glucose_level < quantile(newdata$avg_glucose_level,0.25) - 1.5*iqr1 |

length(glucose_outliers)/nrow(newdata)*100
## [1] 12.27006

Observations: count of the outliers which are present in the average glucose level is very much high, to be exact we have 12% of data are considered as outliers.

t-test for numerical variables

t_test = c()
target = newdata$stroke
num_cols = c("age","avg_glucose_level","bmi")

for (x in num_cols)
{
  t = t.test(newdata[,x] ~ target)
  t_test[x] = t$p.value
}


t_test = as.matrix(t_test)
colnames(t_test) = "p-value"
View(t_test)

Observations: Above three numerical variables p value is less than 0.05. We can say that these are significant.

Chi-square test for categorical variables

chi_square = c()
target = newdata$stroke

cat_cols = c("gender","hypertension","heart_disease","ever_married","work_type",
         "Residence_type","smoking_status")

for (y in cat_cols)
{
  chi = chisq.test(table(newdata[,y] , target))
  chi_square[y] = chi$p.value
}
## Warning in chisq.test(table(newdata[, y], target)): Chi-squared approximation
## may be incorrect

## Warning in chisq.test(table(newdata[, y], target)): Chi-squared approximation
## may be incorrect
chi_square = as.matrix(chi_square)
colnames(chi_square) = "p-value"
View(chi_square)

Observations: Gender and Residence type p-values are more than 0.05 and remaining other category variables are less than 0.05. Therefore we do not consider Gender and residence type variables for the model.
